---
import Layout from '../../../../layouts/Base.astro';
import Repl from '../../../../components/Repl';
import SchemeRepl from '../../../../components/SchemeRepl';
import PrevNext from "../../../../components/PrevNext.astro";
---

<Layout title="Logic Ch.2 — Propositional Logic Syntax" favicon="🔑">
  <main>

    <a href="/reading/logic/" class="text-sm mb-4 inline-block">&larr; back to logic</a>

    <h1>Propositional Logic Syntax</h1>
    <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mb-6">Craig DeLancey &middot; A Concise Introduction to Logic, Ch. 2 &middot; <a href="https://milneopentextbooks.org/a-concise-introduction-to-logic/">CC BY-SA 4.0</a></p>

    <div class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-5 mb-8 callout">
      <p class="text-lg" style="max-width:none">Propositional logic has <strong>atomic propositions</strong> (P, Q, R) and five <strong>connectives</strong>: not, and, or, implies, iff. A <strong>well-formed formula</strong> is built recursively from these pieces. Parsing a formula means finding its structure.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- SVG: Parse tree for (P and Q) implies R -->
    <div class="flex justify-center my-6">
      <svg viewBox="0 0 300 180" class="w-full max-w-sm" style="font-family: ui-monospace, monospace;">
        <!-- Root: implies -->
        <text x="150" y="30" text-anchor="middle" fill="#f59e0b" font-size="14">&rarr;</text>
        <!-- Left child: and -->
        <line x1="140" y1="35" x2="80" y2="70" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1" stroke-opacity="0.4"/>
        <text x="75" y="80" text-anchor="middle" fill="#60a5fa" font-size="14">&and;</text>
        <!-- Right child: R -->
        <line x1="160" y1="35" x2="220" y2="70" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1" stroke-opacity="0.4"/>
        <text x="225" y="80" text-anchor="middle" fill="currentColor" font-size="14" fill-opacity="0.7">R</text>
        <!-- Left-left: P -->
        <line x1="68" y1="85" x2="40" y2="120" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1" stroke-opacity="0.4"/>
        <text x="35" y="130" text-anchor="middle" fill="currentColor" font-size="14" fill-opacity="0.7">P</text>
        <!-- Left-right: Q -->
        <line x1="82" y1="85" x2="110" y2="120" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1" stroke-opacity="0.4"/>
        <text x="115" y="130" text-anchor="middle" fill="currentColor" font-size="14" fill-opacity="0.7">Q</text>
        <!-- Caption -->
        <text x="150" y="170" text-anchor="middle" fill="currentColor" font-size="10" fill-opacity="0.35">Parse tree for (P &and; Q) &rarr; R</text>
      </svg>
    </div>

    <h3>Atomic propositions</h3>
    <p>An atomic proposition is a statement that is either true or false, with no internal logical structure. We use capital letters P, Q, R as variables standing for any proposition.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; Atomic propositions: just symbols
; We represent them as Scheme symbols

(define P (quote P))
(define Q (quote Q))
(define R (quote R))

(display "Atomic propositions: ")
(display (list P Q R))
`} />

    <h3>Connectives</h3>
    <p>The five connectives build compound formulas from simpler ones.</p>

    <div class="overflow-x-auto my-4">
      <table class="w-full text-sm">
        <thead>
          <tr class="border-b border-zinc-700">
            <th class="py-2 pr-4">Symbol</th>
            <th class="py-2 pr-4">Name</th>
            <th class="py-2 pr-4">English</th>
            <th class="py-2">Arity</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr class="border-b border-zinc-800"><td class="py-2 pr-4 font-mono">&not;</td><td class="pr-4">Negation</td><td class="pr-4">not P</td><td>1 (unary)</td></tr>
          <tr class="border-b border-zinc-800"><td class="py-2 pr-4 font-mono">&and;</td><td class="pr-4">Conjunction</td><td class="pr-4">P and Q</td><td>2 (binary)</td></tr>
          <tr class="border-b border-zinc-800"><td class="py-2 pr-4 font-mono">&or;</td><td class="pr-4">Disjunction</td><td class="pr-4">P or Q</td><td>2 (binary)</td></tr>
          <tr class="border-b border-zinc-800"><td class="py-2 pr-4 font-mono">&rarr;</td><td class="pr-4">Conditional</td><td class="pr-4">if P then Q</td><td>2 (binary)</td></tr>
          <tr><td class="py-2 pr-4 font-mono">&harr;</td><td class="pr-4">Biconditional</td><td class="pr-4">P if and only if Q</td><td>2 (binary)</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <h3>Well-formed formulas</h3>
    <p>A <strong>well-formed formula</strong> (wff) is defined recursively: every atom is a wff. If A is a wff, then (not A) is a wff. If A and B are wffs, then (A and B), (A or B), (A implies B), and (A iff B) are wffs. Nothing else is a wff.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; Formulas as S-expressions (already trees!)
; (not P)
; (and P Q)
; (or P Q)
; (implies P Q)
; (iff P Q)

; Check if something is a well-formed formula
(define (atom? x) (symbol? x))

(define (wff? f)
  (cond
    ((atom? f) #t)
    ((not (list? f)) #f)
    ((and (= (length f) 2) (equal? (car f) (quote neg)))
     (wff? (cadr f)))
    ((and (= (length f) 3)
          (member (car f) (list (quote and) (quote or)
                                (quote implies) (quote iff))))
     (and (wff? (cadr f)) (wff? (caddr f))))
    (else #f)))

; Test
(display "(implies (and P Q) R) is wff? ")
(display (wff? (list (quote implies) (list (quote and) (quote P) (quote Q)) (quote R)))) (newline)

(display "(and P) is wff? ")
(display (wff? (list (quote and) (quote P)))) (newline)

(display "P is wff? ")
(display (wff? (quote P)))
`} />

    <div class="python-block my-2" style="display:none">
      <Repl client:visible initialCode={`# Formulas as nested tuples
# ("not", P)  ("and", P, Q)  ("implies", P, Q)

def is_wff(f):
    if isinstance(f, str):
        return True  # atom
    if not isinstance(f, tuple):
        return False
    if len(f) == 2 and f[0] == "not":
        return is_wff(f[1])
    if len(f) == 3 and f[0] in ("and", "or", "implies", "iff"):
        return is_wff(f[1]) and is_wff(f[2])
    return False

print(f'("implies", ("and", "P", "Q"), "R"): {is_wff(("implies", ("and", "P", "Q"), "R"))}')
print(f'("and", "P"): {is_wff(("and", "P"))}')
print(f'"P": {is_wff("P")}')
`} />
    </div>

    <h3>Parsing</h3>
    <p>Parsing a formula means recovering its tree structure. The <strong>main connective</strong> is the root of the parse tree: the last connective applied. For (P &and; Q) &rarr; R, the main connective is &rarr; because implication was applied last.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; The main connective is the outermost operator
(define (main-connective f)
  (if (symbol? f)
    (quote atom)
    (car f)))

(define formula (list (quote implies) (list (quote and) (quote P) (quote Q)) (quote R)))

(display "Formula: ") (display formula) (newline)
(display "Main connective: ") (display (main-connective formula)) (newline)

; Subformulas
(display "Left subformula: ") (display (cadr formula)) (newline)
(display "Right subformula: ") (display (caddr formula))
`} />

    <PrevNext prev={{ href: "/reading/logic/logic-01/", label: "Arguments and Validity" }} next={{ href: "/reading/logic/logic-03/", label: "Truth Tables" }} />

  </main>
</Layout>
